  abstract = {The changes of diet that reached the rural masses of European countries in the middle of the 19th century arrived late in Southern Italy. They began to appear towards the end of the century, but were neither a direct effect of the schanges brought about in the agrarian structure by reforms nor an immediate consequence of capitalist development in the countryside. They were essentially the result of a demographic and social phenomenon of vast proportions: overseas emigration between the 1800s and the 1900s. A model case, apart from some regional peculiarities, is represented by the story of the Calabrian peasants, whose diet changed as a result of the impact with different food standards. In Brasil, Argentina and the USA, meat consumption was to break a century-old vegetarian diet. Previously unknown products such as tea, beer and cocoa entered the daily diet. But even at home, thanks to the emigrants' remittances, the rise in salaries and the changes in social and cultural relations, there were appreciable and at times quite considerable novelties in this field.}
